    "body": "When converting a Python int to any C integral type, Cython checks the data type's limits and may raise `OverflowError`. But it doesn't do the same when converting to a 32-bit float, because it simply has:\r\n\r\n`#define __pyx_PyFloat_AsFloat(x) ((float) __pyx_PyFloat_AsDouble(x))`\r\n\r\n",
    "closed_at": "2017-05-19T17:30:05Z",
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "body": "There are no data type limits for 32-bit floats, only limited precision, and when casting to a float it's explicit that precision is lost. Positive and negative infinity are used as approximations for values that are outside the range that can be finitely represented, and that's correct for this context as well. \r\n\r\n(FWIW, unless you're memory-bound, there's little reason these days to use 32-bit floats and lots of reasons not to.)",
            "created_at": "2017-05-19T16:51:52Z",
